Motivation and Background

Give an overview of the project, motivation, background and goals.

Counter Strike: Global Offensive, CSGO for short, has been the bread and butter of Esports for 9 years. CSGO is a 5v5 tactical First-Person-Shooter. Teams compete against each other in different CSGO maps, where one team plays as the Terrorists and the other as Counter-Terrorists, each with different game objectives. Teams buy weapons based off of their economy, which is affected by their personal performance as well as round wins.

I have been playing CSGO for nearly 5 years and despite the times where I "swear I will never play this trash game ever again", I still find myself coming back to this game that I love.

I love the game mostly for 2 reasons:

  1. Its competitive

    • There is little places where RNG affects the outcome of the match. If you win, it is because you played better, made better decisions, it is rarely due to luck that a round goes one way rather than the other.

  2. Its complex

    • The rounds are varied. No two rounds are played out the same way as the other, leading to many unique outcomes despite having the same, equal and fair start across all matches, where teams start out with the same health and economy.
    • The skill ceiling is very high, almost limitless. Players have to improve on both their micro (aiming, movement) and macro (gamesense, strategies) skills to be able to compete at the highest level.

So, I want to explore on the trends of professional players, the patterns in the games by using Data Analytics to gain a deeper insight, albeit one that is still quite shallow as compared to real CSGO analysts VOD-reviewing the gameplay itself and studying the teams, players, and their decisions frame by frame.

The data in this project will be via web-scraping of the HLTV website. HLTV is the main platform to gain information of professional matches in CSGO, and is free for everyone to view all the content, which is good for web-scraping. (Sort of like LiveScore in football.)

Summary of Research Questions & Results

Repeat your research questions in a numbered list. After each research question, clearly state the answer/conclusion you determined. Do not give details or justifications yet just the answer

  1. What makes a good entry fragger?

    • Is a good entry fragger one that just wins more opening duels? What if these opening kills are not impactful?
    • Does entry fragging mean they sacrifice their ability to get multikills for the greater good of the team?

  2. How does pressure and experience affect performance?

    • Different people react differently when faced with pressure. In a LAN match or a Major event, the conditions are very different as compared to playing an online match.
    • I want to compare how players fare in these conditions, if it makes a difference at all based on their experience.

  3. How does age impact a player's performance, and their role in a team?

    • It is a common stigma that older players are "slower to react" than younger players, and that the lifespan of esports players are very short.
    • So does age differences truly make a difference in game? Or are the roles of the players spread evenly across the ages?

  4. How does different sides affect a role's flashes and pistol rounds?

    • T and CT sides have different objectives and different advantages to win the round. I want to see how the sides affects their utility usage in flashes, as well as in pistol rounds.

  5. How does a player's role affect their performance?

    • A player could be an AWPer, or a Rifler, which affects their playstyles due to the nature of the weapons, being that the AWP is a one shot bodyshot kill, allowing them to get easier kills, but have a longer drawout time and lower firerate than rifles. How do these factors affect their performance in game?

Dataset

Numbered list of dataset (with downloadable links) and a brief but clear description of each dataset used. Draw reference to the numbering when describing methodology (data cleaning and analysis).

  1. https://www.hltv.org/

    Web-scraping will be done on this site to gather more data on various statistics, such as player rating, player Kill-Death Ratio (K/D), team round win percent (RW%) and many other statistics. See the Jupyter Notebook HLTV Web Scraper.ipynb for source code.

Methodology

There is only one source of data and it is from HLTV. HLTV holds the monopoly in CSGO esports data, and has information on 10 years of player data. Firstly I will web scrape data off from the website from the respective pages as well as individual player pages (for more descriptive data). Due to the website having a rate limit as well as including some anomalies in table entries, I will split the web scraping of individual players into chunks by saving web scraped data periodically while scraping to reduce the time taken to scrape all of the data, so that when an error occurs or a rate limit is reached, some of the data is already saved and I do not need to start scraping from square one again.

After scraping the data, I will import it and combine the many CSV files into their own dataframes. Afterwards I will clean the data by accounting for NaN values as well as the website's version of NaN values saved as other strings, such as dashes ('-'), while dropping columns that are irrelevant and repetitive.

At the end, EDA will be performed on each group of dataframes, followed by improving upon graphs in the EDA inside Results and Conclusion.

import os
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
WEB_SCRAPED = "Web Scraped"
CAREER = f"{WEB_SCRAPED}/players_career"
INDIVIDUAL = f"{WEB_SCRAPED}/players_individual"
OVERVIEW = f"{WEB_SCRAPED}/players_overview"

This dataframe contains the ratings of each player across different types of matches. Each row is a player. The index is "name" referring to each player's in-game-name (aka IGN). "hltv_id" is not really relevant here, but is useful to access the player's individual webpage on hltv.org.

Online refers to matches played online, where players experience ping differences due to the latency of information being transmitted from a player's inputs at their computers to the CSGO server itself. Often, players play in the comfort of their own homes or in a bootcamp organised by their respective organisations, meant to simulate the environment of a LAN event.

A LAN event, or a Local-Area-Network event, in this case refers to CSGO matches played on the same LAN, resulting to negligible ping/latency, so that the match played is more fair. The pressure is also higher at LAN events/matches, since most requires teams to qualify through playing multiple qualifier matches. At LAN events, there is usually an audience too, which only makes it more nerve wracking for some people.

Majors are only for the cream of the crop, where they are only held once per year, with the top teams competing against each other on the biggest stage CSGO has to offer, with a massive live audience in a stadium, an average of almost 300 thousand viewers online, and prize pools worth a million dollars. Needless to say this is the most important event in CSGO, and major winners are highly regarded by the players.

  • "X-rating" refers to the the rating of the player in that type of matches played. For example, "all-rating" means rating across all maps played across all events, whether it be online, LAN, or in a Major.

  • "X-maps" refers to the number of maps played by the player within that type of match. For example, "majors-maps" refers to the number of maps played in CSGO Major events.

This dataframe contains the specific information of each individual player.

Opening kills are the first kills in a round, which is arguably the most important one as it sets the tempo for the rest of the round. A 5v4 in favor of your team is a huge bonus from a 5v5, since the enemies need to play much better in order to make up for the lower manpower.

  • "o_total_k" refers to total opening kills a player has gotten.
  • "o_total_d" refers to the total opening deaths a player has gotten.
  • "o_ratio" is the ratio of total opening kills to deaths.
  • "o_rating" refers to the rating of how good the player is at getting opening kills, based on a metric designed by HLTV
  • "o_win%" refers to the chances of the player's team winning after they got their opening kill.
  • "o_won_rounds" refers to the percentage of rounds the team won where the player has gotten a first kill.

Each round starts off as a 5v5, so a player can kill anywhere between 0 and 5 players (inclusive) each round. There are no revives.

  • "rounds_Xk" means number of rounds the player had X number of kills.

Every round players buy weapons to increase their firepower and their chances of winning the round. Each weapon can be classified under either Rifle, Sniper, SMG (sub-machine gun), Pistols, Grenades or Other.

  • "X_k" refers to number of kills with X weapon. For example, "rifle_k" means number of kills this player has using the rifle.

This dataframe contains the more general information of each player.

  • "age" is a measure of their real life age.

  • "team" refers to the team that they represent in matches currently. (Some have no team as they have either retired or moved on to other jobs.)

  • "rating" is a measure of how good a player is based on a metric designed by HLTV, taking into account of the following statistics.

  • "DPR" is short for Deaths Per Round, it refers to the deaths per round of the player.

  • "KAST" is short for Kill/Assist/Survived/Traded, which measures the percentage of rounds where a player has done any of the 4 aforementioned things. You could say this measures a player's consistent impact throughout the match.

  • "impact" measures how impactful the player is when getting opening kills, multi-kills, and clutches.

  • "ADR" is short for Average Damager per Round a measure of how much damage a player deals every round.

  • "KPR" is short for Kills Per Round the number of kills a player gets per round.

The following 3 dataframes contain information on flashes. A flashbang grenade is a utility that can be bought every round, and it is very powerful. If a player much better than you is fighting a 1v1 against you, a well placed flashbang will win you the round by blinding the opponent long enough for you to take your time to hit the headshot.

Each dataframe correspond to a different set of data, one from flashes thrown as Counter-Terrorists, one from Terrorists, and one for both combined.

  • "Maps" refers to total maps played by the player.

  • "Rounds" refer to total rounds played by the player.

  • "Thrown" means the number of flashes thrown per round on average.

  • "Blinded" refers to how long the player themselves were blinded for every round.

  • "Opp Flashed" refers to how long the opponents are blinded for by this player every round.

  • "Diff" is the difference between the time the opponents were flashed and the time the player themselves were blinded for per round.

  • "FA" refers to flash assists per round. A flash assist happens when an opponent blinded by this player was killed while affected by the flash.

  • "Success" refers to flash success, how many opponents were flashed for every flashbang thrown.

As mentioned previously, opening kills are crucial to the round, and more or less determines the pace of the round afterwards. The following 3 dataframes contain information on opening kills.

Each dataframe correspond to a different set of data, one from opening kills as Counter-Terrorists, one from Terrorists, and one for both combined.

  • "Maps" refers to total maps played by the player.

  • "Rounds" refers to total rounds played by the player.

  • "KPR" refers to opening kills per round.

  • "DPR" refers to opening deaths per round.

  • "Attempts" refers to percentage of rounds where the player is involved in an opening kill or opening death. (% of rounds where a player "entried")

  • "Success" refers to the success rate of players when they do take the opening duel.

  • "Rating" is a measure of how good a player is at getting opening kills, which is similar to entry-fragging.

Delegating roles to players based on their ratio of rifle kills to sniper kills. In a team, there is generally a dedicated AWPer who uses the sniper to get more kills for the team, with 4 other riflers to support the AWPer.

In[19]:
gun_k = players.loc[:, "rifle_k": "other_k"].sum().sort_values()
rifle_sniper_ratio = gun_k["rifle_k"] / gun_k["sniper_k"]
players["rifle_sniper_ratio"] = players["rifle_k"] / players["sniper_k"]
players["role"] = np.nan
def player_role(row):
    if row["rifle_sniper_ratio"] > rifle_sniper_ratio:
        row["role"] = "Rifler"
    else:
        row["role"] = "Awper"
    return row
    
players = players.apply(player_role, axis="columns")
players

Research Question 1: What makes a good entry fragger?

Entry fraggers are the catalysts to the rounds. They get the round started by making space for the team, going in first before anyone else to gain more information. This role is the most dangerous role in the team, as they are the first contact to the enemies.

Different players have different playstyles, so not every player is cut out to be the entry fragger. However, how do we measure whether it is worth it for X player to entry frag? Their impact on the round is more than just their kills. They contribute by creating space for their teammates, and even their deaths are valuable since the second player can trade their deaths by killing the enemy.

Research Question 4: How does different sides affect a role's flashes and pistol rounds?

In CSGO, terrorists (T) attack bombsites (2 bombsites per map) in order to plant the bomb. T wins if they either kill all the counter-terrorists (CT) before the round time runs out, or if they plant the bomb and prevent the CT from defusing the bomb before it explodes.

CT defend bombsites and prevent T from winning by stalling for time so that they cannot plant, eliminating all the T, or by successfully defusing the bomb.

Since the bombsites are placed closer to CT spawn, CTs play a defensive game, waiting for T to push into them most of the time. Whereas T plays a more offensive game, forced to push into CT to win rounds.

The guns and their prices are also slightly different on each side. A notable difference is in the primary rifle. On CT you can buy a M4A4 (or M4A1-S alternatively), which does not guarantee a one headshot kill, while on T you can buy an AK47 for cheaper, with a lower firerate but a one headshot kill.

I want to investigate how playing different sides affect how a rifler, awper, entry fragger or support player's performance in terms of their flash utility and pistol round stats.

A trend can be seen where the gradient increases from the scatterplot of 0 kills to 5 kills, which shows how more attempts means a generally higher proportion of rounds with multikills.

It could also be that due to the entry fragger getting the first kill most of the time, leaving less enemies for their teammates to kill, whereas the entry fragger is already ahead by 1 kill. A good entry fragger is also one that attempts opening duels often, thus challenging the opponents and create space for the team. Since a good entry fragger means that they attempt more opening duels more often, they also tend to get more multikills in their matches.

Similarly, a cone shape can be seen in this graph, however this cone is less symmetrical along the line y=0. Players generally have a large decrease in their performance/rating when moving from LAN to Major, however experience still helps in keeping a consistent performance throughout at near 0% change in rating. It could also be that at Major events, the pressure is much higher, resulting in poorer performances. However, these conclusions could be incorrect due to Majors being only played by the top of the top players, which may cause mediocre players to suffer a much lower rating due to playing against players of the highest calibre. As a result, the change in rating is more so due to the opponents, and not the players themselves.

In conclusion, playing more maps and having more experience is key to maintaining a consistent performance in big events, as shown clearly in the plots above, since playing more maps decreases the fluctuaction of their rating from the other events. Pressure is likely to be a huge factor in performance, one that negatively affects the players as seen in the third figure, where many players had a decrease in rating from LAN rating to Major rating.

age_role = players[["age", "role"]].value_counts().to_frame(name="count").reset_index()

Research Question 5: How does a player's role affect their performance?

In[63]:

As can be seen from this violinplot, Awpers tend to have a higher rating than Riflers, where it has a higher median as well as a higher inter-quartile range. This could be due to the fact that Awpers have an easier time getting kills, due to Awp only requiring a bodyshot to kill, while rifle requires a few bodyshots or a headshot to kill. In[64]:
pivot = players.groupby(["role"]).sum().loc[:, "rounds_0k":"rounds_5k"]
pivot = pivot / pivot.sum()
pivot.T.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(12,10))

plt.legend(loc="upper left", ncol=2)
plt.xlabel("Number of kills in a round")
plt.ylabel("Proportion")


for n, x in enumerate([*pivot.T.index.values]):
    for proportion in pivot.T.loc[x]:
                
        plt.text(x=n,
                 y=proportion,
                 s=f'{np.round(proportion * 100, 1)}%', 
                 color="black",
                 fontsize=12,
                 fontweight="bold")
plt.title("Tendency of Awpers VS Riflers to get multikill rounds")
plt.show()

There is little correlation of roles to number of kills in a round. However, one may argue that Awpers tend to get slightly more multikills as the percentage increases from 25.5% in rounds with 0 kills to 26.9% in rounds with 4 kills for Awpers.

This shows that the role of the player does not significantly affect how likely it is for players to get multikills.

In conclusion, the role of the player does affect their HLTV rating, as AWPers tend to get higher ratings than Riflers, which may be caused by the nature of the weapon, or by teams placing skilled players on the role of the AWPer.

The role however does not affect their performance in terms of multikills in a round.
